In order to reflect properly on the Database and Web Systems Odyssey experience and how it teaches the concept of service, I feel that I need to write more personally than I have in other blog posts.

When I initially approached the Computer Science major, I fell into the belief that this was the major that you pick if you want to sit in front of a computer and avoid as much interaction with others as possible. I remember being a High School freshman and watching videos of the lifestyles of Software Developers, Web Developers, and Cybersecurity Professionals. In all of these glorified portrayals of the job, the person recording their “day in the life” worked from home, magically receiving work to do through a screen, only sitting through a meeting with others virtually for about 30 minutes a day. Obviously, many people may see this as an isolationist lifestyle, but for a younger version of myself, I saw it as the ideal career. Flashing forward to this course, alongside many other courses that I’ve taken in pursuit of my degree, I can validate that those jobs do exist. However, jobs like that exist only because someone else has removed the programmer-client interaction by doing it for you. You have no connection to the client, and thus, no connection to the work you are doing other than your biweekly paycheck. This course helped me to see the overwhelming value in that relationship by working actively with Ms. Nora Simmons and Dr. Peter Kett to create a new web page for the Hendrix Medical School Applications pipeline.

## Skills

Working with others, especially in a client-based relationship, was not new to me in the sense that I have worked numerous jobs over the summers where my clientele ranges from retail customers all the way through the citizens of Arkansas for the State government. However, what was new was the context in which my team and I operated. Rather than clocking in for a 40-hour work week, we needed to manage time effectively, generating time to communicate, develop, and present our project to both our class and our community partner. Additionally, we as a group had to recognize that our availabilities and additional commitments may not align with one another, creating an extra layer of complexity when planning to work together or with Ms. Simmons. Beyond the issues in my personal life, this was still difficult. I’m quite used to planning and working only for myself or academia. Thus, patience, humility, and transparency needed to be at the forefront of my relationship with my group and our client. If I failed to do something, I needed to admit it. If I did not communicate with my team properly and we misunderstood each other, I needed to admit it. If I was frustrated with another teammate or with myself, I needed to be professional and admit my faults, but prioritize the group and project environment. Everything about this project challenged what I believed I was comfortable with. I believed I was a person who met deadlines, and I missed them. I believed I was a person who learned quickly, yet I spent most of my time learning from my group members. And lastly, I believed this project would be easy, but it required me to face all of these internal notions of my own skillset and experience in addition to the workload.

## Focus

I feel that this project was less about addressing a spiritual, environmental, or social need and more about improving someone’s quality of life. Ms. Simmons has been trapped under the boulder of a horrific workflow for far too long. By completing this project, I feel that we may have improved her quality of life, which in turn allows her to spend more of her time doing what she wants to do with her life. The project was not designed to program her out of a job, but free her from the tedium that it entailed. Thus, I believe that by asking for help in this field, Ms. Simmons has improved her workflow and, therefore, the timeline for students to receive recommendation letters to Medical School.

## Values

While I don’t believe that any of my fundamental values have changed, I believe that my understanding of work and its relationship with humanity has. As I mentioned earlier, I did not see this work as socially interactive, but that was entirely wrong. Every website, line of code, or client meeting reveals a level of humanity. By being an active part of my group and the relationship with our client, I understand what it feels like to be passionate about completing something for someone else’s benefit. I’m happy that I’ve had this experience, as I feel that it filled in and created its own fundamental value: a sense of service to others, utilizing your skillset.

## Call to Action

For me, this project did not make me interested in conquering a social issue, nor a political one. It taught me more about humanity. I can honestly say that I don’t see myself working for some large remote mega-corporation with only 30 minutes of interaction per day. I want to care about the work. I want to work on projects for people that I care about. And thus, I feel that this experience has called me to look for the humanity in everything that I do. Everything is designed for humans in the tech world. Sometimes, though, we get lost in the ones and zeroes, scrambling for a paycheck.